    <exercise number="13.1.1">
      <p>
        What is the domain of <m>\v{r}(t) = e^t\v{i} + \dfrac{1}{t}\v{j} + (t + 1)^{-3}\v{k}</m>? 
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\v{r}(t)</m> is defined for <m>t\neq 0</m> and <m>t \neq -1</m>, hence the domain of <m>\v{r}(t)</m> is 
          <md>
            D = \left\{t \in \R \mid t\neq 0 \text{ and } t\neq -1 \right\}
          </md>
          
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="13.1.5">
      <p>
        Find a vector parametrization of the line through <m>P = (3,-5,7)</m> in the direction <m>\v{v} = \la 3,0,1 \ra</m>. 
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          We use the vector parametrization of the line to obtain
          <md>
            <mrow> \v{r}(t) \amp= \overrightarrow{OP} + t\v{v} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \la 3, -5, 7 \ra + t\la 3, 0, 1 \ra </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \la 3 + 3t, -5, 7 + t \ra </mrow>
          </md>
          or in the form of
          <md>
            \v{r}(t) = \lp 3 + 3t \rp \v{i} - 5\v{j} + \lp 7 + t \rp\v{k}
          </md>
          
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="13.1.7">
      <p>
        Determine whether the space curve given by <m>\v{r}(t) = \la \sin(t), \dfrac{\cos(t)}{2}, t \ra</m> intersects the <m>z</m>-axis, and if it does, determine where. 
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The curve intersects the <m>z</m>-axis if there is some value of <m>t</m> such that both the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>-coordinates of <m>\v{r}(t)</m> are zero. 
          That is, such that <m>\sin(t) = \cos\lp\frac{t}{2}\rp = 0</m>. 
          Now, <m>\sin(x) = 0</m> when <m>x = n\pi</m>, while <m>\cos(x) = 0</m> when <m>x = \frac{\pi}{2} + n\pi = \frac{2n+1}{2}\pi</m>, where <m>n</m> is an integer.
          So if <m>t = k\pi</m>, then <m>\sin(t) = 0</m>, and if, further, <m>k = 2n + 1</m> is odd, then <m>\cos\lp\frac{k}{2}\pi\rp = 0</m>.
          So this curve intersects the <m>z</m>-axis whenever <m>k</m> is an odd integer multiple of <m>\pi</m>, at the points <m>\lp 0,0,(2n + 1)\pi \rp</m>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

