      <exercise number="13.1.19">
        <p>
          <m>\v{r}(t) = (9\cos(t))\v{i} + (9\sin(t))\v{j}</m>
        </p>

        <solution>
          <p>
            Since <m>x(t) = 9\cos(t)</m> and <m>y(t) = 9\sin(t)</m>, we have 
            <md>
              x^2 + y^2 = 81\cos^2(t) + 81\sin^2(t) = 81\lp\cos^2(t) + \sin^2(t)\rp = 81
            </md> 
            This is the equation of a circle with radius <m>9</m> centered at the origin. 
            The circle lies in the <m>xy</m>-\plane. 
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise number="13.1.21">
        <p>
          <m>\v{r}(t) = \la \sin(t), 0, 4+\cos(t) \ra</m>
        </p>

        <solution>
          <p>
            Since <m>x(t) = \sin(t)</m> and <m>z(t) = 4 + \cos(t)</m>, we have 
            <md>
              x^2 + (z-4)^2 = \sin^2(t) + \cos^2(t) = 1
            </md>
            <m>y = 0</m> is the equation of the <m>xz</m>-plane. 
            We conclude that. the function traces the circle of radius <m>1</m>, centered at th epoint <m>(0,0,4)</m>, and contained in the <m>xz</m>-plane. 
