    <exercise number="13.1.25">
      <p>
        Let <m>\c{C}</m> be the curve given by <m>\v{r}(t) = \la t\cos(t), t\sin(t), t \ra</m>. 
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that <m>\c{C}</m> lies on the cone <m>x^2 + y^2 = z^2</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Sketch the cone and make a rough sketch of <m>\c{C}</m> on the cone. 
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <solution>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              We have <m>x(t) = t\cos(t)</m>, <m>y(t) = t\sin(t)</m>, and <m>z(t) = t</m>. 
              Hence for any point <m>(x,y,z)</m> on the curve, we obtain
              <md>
                <mrow> x^2 + y^2 \amp= t^2 \cos^2(t) + t^2 \sin^2(t) </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp= t^2 \lp \cos^2(t) + \sin^2(t) \rp </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp= t^2 </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp= z^2 </mrow>
              </md>
              Thus the curve lies on the circular cone whose equation is <m>x^2 + y^2 = z^2</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              As the height <m>z = t</m> increases linearly with time, the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> coordinates trace out points on the circles of increasing radius. 
              We obtain the following curve. 
            </p>

            <figure>
              <caption>The Sketch of the Curve <m>\v{r}(t) = \la t\cos(t), t\sin(t), t \ra</m>. </caption>
              <interactive xml:id="interactive-conical-helix-centered" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
                <slate surface="sage">
                  var('t')
                  # 1. Define the curve (including negative t for negative z)
                  r = (t*cos(t), t*sin(t), t)
                  curve = parametric_plot3d(r, (t, -4*pi, 4*pi), thickness=3, color='blue')
                  
                  # 2. Create standard axes crossing at (0,0,0)
                  # We draw arrows manually because standard 'axes=True' often relies on the frame borders in 3D
                  ax_limit = 14
                  x_axis = arrow3d((-ax_limit, 0, 0), (ax_limit, 0, 0), color='black', thickness=1)
                  y_axis = arrow3d((0, -ax_limit, 0), (0, ax_limit, 0), color='black', thickness=1)
                  z_axis = arrow3d((0, 0, -ax_limit), (0, 0, ax_limit), color='black', thickness=1)
                  
                  # 3. Add labels for x, y, z
                  x_label = text3d("x", (ax_limit + 1, 0, 0), color='black')
                  y_label = text3d("y", (0, ax_limit + 1, 0), color='black')
                  z_label = text3d("z", (0, 0, ax_limit + 1), color='black')
                  
                  # 4. Combine and show without the box frame
                  total_plot = curve + x_axis + y_axis + z_axis + x_label + y_label + z_label
                  total_plot.show(frame=False)
                </slate>
              </interactive>
            </figure>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="13.1.29">
      <p>
        Parametrize the part of the intersection of the surfaces
        <md>
          y^2 - z^2 = x - 2\, , \qquad y^2 + z^2 = 9
        </md>
        where <m>z \geq 0</m> using <m>t = y</m> as the parameter. 
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          We solve for <m>z</m> and <m>x</m> in terms of <m>y</m>. 
          From the equation <m>y^2 + z^2 = 9</m>, we have <m>z^2 = 9 - y^2</m>, so <m>z = \pm \sqrt{9 - y^2}</m>. 
          From the second equation, we have
          <md>
            <mrow> x \amp= y^2 - z^2 + 2 </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= y^2 - \lp 9 - y^2 \rp + 2 </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= 2y^2 - 7 </mrow>
          </md>
          Taking <m>t = y</m> as a parameter, we have 
          <md>
            z = \pm \sqrt{9 - t^2} \qquad \text{ and } \qquad x = 2t^2 - 7
          </md>
          yielding the following vector parametrization 
          <md>
            \v{r}(t) = \la 2t^2 - 7, t, \pm \sqrt{9 - t^2} \ra \, , \quad \text{for } -3 \leq t \leq 3
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="13.1.33">
      <p>
        Use sine and cosine to parametrize the intersection of the cylinder <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m> and the plane <m>x + y + z = 1</m>. 
        Then describe the projections of this curve onto the three coordinate planes. 
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          To parametrize the intersection, we start with the cylinder equation <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m>. 
          This suggests using polar coordinates for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>. Let <m>x = \cos(t)</m> and <m>y = \sin(t)</m> for <m>0 \leq t \leq 2\pi</m>.
          
        </p>
        <p>
          We find the <m>z</m> component by substituting these into the equation of the plane <m>x + y + z = 1</m>:
          <md>
            z = 1 - x - y = 1 - \cos(t) - \sin(t)
          </md>
          Thus, the vector parametrization is:
          <md>
            \v{r}(t) = \la \cos(t), \sin(t), 1 - \cos(t) - \sin(t) \ra
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          The projections onto the coordinate planes are found by eliminating the variable corresponding to the axis perpendicular to that plane:
          <ul>
            <li>
              <title>The <m>xy</m>-plane (<m>z=0</m>)</title>
              <p>
                The projection is the unit circle <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>The <m>xz</m>-plane (<m>y=0</m>)</title>
              <p>
                We eliminate <m>y</m> using the plane equation <m>y = 1 - x - z</m> and substitute it into the cylinder equation. 
                The projection is the ellipse given by <m>x^2 + (1 - x - z)^2 = 1</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>The <m>yz</m>-plane (<m>x=0</m>)</title>
              <p>
                We eliminate <m>x</m> using the plane equation <m>x = 1 - y - z</m> and substitute it into the cylinder equation. 
                The projection is the ellipse given by <m>(1 - y - z)^2 + y^2 = 1</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="13.1.37">
      <p>
        Two paths <m>\v{r}_1(t)</m> and <m>\v{r}_2(t)</m> intersect if there is a point <m>P</m> lying on both curves. 
        We say that <m>\v{r}_1(t)</m> and <m>\v{r}_2(t)</m> collide if <m>\v{r}_1(t_0) = \v{r}_2(t_0)</m> at some point <m>t_0</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Determine whether <m>\v{r}_1(t)</m> and <m>\v{r}_2(t)</m> collide or intersect, giving the coordinates of the corresponding points if they exist: 
        <md>
          \v{r}_1(t) = \la t^3+3, t+1, 6t^{-1} \ra\, , \qquad \v{r}_2(t) = \la 4t, 2t-2, t^2-7 \ra
        </md>
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
            <strong>Collision:</strong> We check if there is a time <m>t</m> such that <m>\v{r}_1(t) = \v{r}_2(t)</m>. Equating the components:
            <md>
                <mrow>t^3 + 3 \amp= 4t \implies t^3 - 4t + 3 = 0</mrow>
                <mrow>t + 1 \amp= 2t - 2 \implies t = 3</mrow>
            </md>
            For the <m>y</m>-components to match, we must have <m>t=3</m>. However, testing <m>t=3</m> in the <m>x</m>-equation gives <m>(3)^3 - 4(3) + 3 = 27 - 12 + 3 = 18 \neq 0</m>. 
            Since no single value of <m>t</m> satisfies all equations, the particles do not collide.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Intersection:</strong> We check if the curves share a point by using different parameters <m>t</m> and <m>s</m>. We set <m>\v{r}_1(t) = \v{r}_2(s)</m>:
            <md>
                <mrow>1) \quad t^3 + 3 \amp= 4s</mrow>
                <mrow>2) \quad t + 1 \amp= 2s - 2</mrow>
                <mrow>3) \quad \frac{6}{t} \amp= s^2 - 7</mrow>
            </md>
            From equation (2), we solve for <m>s</m>: <m>2s = t + 3 \implies s = \frac{t+3}{2}</m>. 
            Substituting this into equation (1):
            <md>
                t^3 + 3 = 4\lp\frac{t+3}{2}\rp = 2(t+3) = 2t + 6
            </md>
            <md>
                t^3 - 2t - 3 = 0
            </md>
            Substituting <m>s = \frac{t+3}{2}</m> into equation (3):
            <md>
              \frac{6}{t} = \lp\frac{t+3}{2}\rp^2 - 7 \implies \frac{24}{t} = (t+3)^2 - 28
            </md>
            Simplifying this yields <m>t^3 + 6t^2 - 19t - 24 = 0</m>. 
            We check the integer roots of this polynomial (<m>t = -1, 3, -8</m>) to see if they satisfy our condition from equation (1), <m>t^3 - 2t - 3 = 0</m>.
            <md>
                \text{If } t = -1: \quad (-1)^3 - 2(-1) - 3 = -2 \neq 0
            </md>
            <md>
                \text{If } t = 3: \quad (3)^3 - 2(3) - 3 = 18 \neq 0
            </md>
            As there is no value <m>t</m> that satisfies the system for all three coordinates, the paths do not intersect.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

